<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-444-976  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 444 976.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ACM restores ties with USSR. (Association for Computing Machinery)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbare E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industrySoviet UnionAssociation of Computing MachineryInternational TradeRegulationLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ACM RESTORES TIES WITH USSR NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A., 1990 MAY 1 (NB) --The Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) has announced that it islifting a 13-year boycott of computer technology exchanges with the SovietUnion.andM;The restoration of ties was announced through the publication of a letterfrom ACM President Bryan Kocher to Evgely Vehilor, head of the ComputerScience Department at the Academy of Sciences in Moscow in which Kocher said:&quot;It is my pleasure to inform you that ACM's Council has rescinded itsprohibition on cooperation with the Soviet Union, which was enacted in 1977.andO;ACM's recognition of the return of the Soviet computer scientists to the fullfellowship of the international scientific community is a direct result ofre-establishment of acceptable levels of scientific freedom for Sovietcomputer scientists, improvement in Soviet respect for the human rights ofits citizens and the citizens of other countries, and reductions of worldtension, which will help computer scientists concentrate on their peacefulpursuits.&quot;andM;The 80,000 member ACM voted in 1977 to boycott all meetings in the SovietUnion and to eliminate scientific exchanges with the country.andP;  This actioncame in response to reports of Soviet repression of the scientific communityand was hailed at the time by Nobel Prize winner and Soviet dissident AndreiSakharov who predicated that the move would eventually aid in forcing theU.S.S.R.andP;  government to give up its repressive policy.andP;  The ACM quotedSakharov as saying: &quot;There is nothing to induce them (the Soviets) sofactually and effectively as a refusal to maintain this cooperation.&quot;andM;ACM spokesperson Jim Adams explained to Newsbytes that the boycott had beenaimed solely at the governments of the repressive countries and not atindividual computer scientists.andP;  &quot;During the period of the boycott, wecontinued to have members from the Soviet Union and other Eastern Europeancountries.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900502/Press Contact: Jim Adams,ACM, 212-869-7440)</TEXT></DOC>